BRARIES AND THE ORGANIZATION OF UNIVERSITIES IN FRANCE, 1789-1881.EXAMINES THE WAYS IN WHICH THE INTERESTS OF PROMOTING LIBRARIES AND THEPROMOTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION CONVERGED IN THE DEVELOPMENT OF FRENCHUNIVERSITY LIBRARIES IN THE 19TH CENTURY. THE REVOLUTION OF 1789 ABOLISHEDUNIVERSITIES AND CONFISCATED THEIR LIBRARIES. THE IMPERIAL UNIVERSITY, ANEDUCATIONAL BUREAUCRACY THAT SURVIVED THE EMPIRE AND ENDURED FOR MOST OF THE19TH CENTURY, DID NOT PROMOTE RESEARCH OR REQUIRE RESEARCH LIBRARIES. HOWEVER,IN 1855 EFFORTS BEGAN TO REPLACE THE IMPERIAL SYSTEM WITH AUTONOMOUSUNIVERSITIES, AND THESE EFFORTS FOCUSED ON THE ROLE OF UNIVERSITY LIBRARIES.IN 1881 UNIVERSITY LIBRARIES WERE CREATED IN THE PROVINCES AS A 1ST STEPTOWARD CREATING UNIVERSITIES, 15 YEARS BEFORE THE DE JURE ESTABLISHMENT OFUNIVERSITIES